<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Chicken Note</div>
<div class="nbunit" id="edn180">  180  That is, <i>Ogham</i>, a sort of deaf-and-dumb alphabet. Joyce had recourse to R.A. Stewart Macalister's <i>The Secret Languages of Ireland</i> (London, l937) while introducing into the chapter a great many allusions to and examples of various Irish &lsquo;secret&rsquo; tongues of former days; that is, languages spoken only among initiates, such as <i>Ogham</i>, <i>Hisperic</i>, <i>Bog Latin</i>, S<i>helta</i>, and <i>Bearlagair na Saer</i>. An account of his use of this book is given in Danis Rose, <i>The Index Manuscript</i>, pages l44-58. One example not previously located, that of the note &ldquo;Satan 1st being to utter God's name&rdquo;, from Macalister's essay on <i>Hisperic</i> (where he cites a stanza in Irish embodying this ancient tradition) can be found at 176.30 (223.27): &lsquo;The howtosayto itiswhatis hemustwhomust worden schall.&rsquo;  </div>
